			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Lost Amulet
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1755627">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<center><b>Chapter 2</b></center><br />
<br />
 <br />
<br />
I awoke with the Sun in my face.  Karima was stirring beside me in the small cot we shared.  The ceiling of the tiny room, a cell really, showed me a square of ordinary blue morning sky, with a few clouds drifting by and the top of the Sun peeking in from the East end.  Last night had been cloudy and nearly Moonless, so perhaps I’d missed falling asleep under the stars with Karima. <br />
<br />
After getting over her surprise at my walking out of that small room with the Arch Magus on my own two feet, she’d become more interested in getting to know me it seems.  According to her, very few Apprenticeship interviews end with the interviewee unscathed.  I’d talked her into accompanying me to the Cup &amp; Plate to try the delightfully strong beer brewed on the premises by the Lady of the House.  We’d staggered back to my room together some time past Midnight, drunk as poets.<br />
<br />
“Anything left of the supper?” murmured Karima.  “I think we just missed breakfast.  I have to get to work, and you have to get ready for your first lessons.  I expect someone will be along any minute to fetch you.”<br />
<br />
“Still some bread and kippers here,” I waved as I swung my legs off the cot and onto the surprisingly warm floor.  There was a light brown robe hanging on a peg on my wall, with a matching skullcap perched on it, and a pair of matching slippers on the floor beneath.  “I suppose Mages don’t wear underwear?”<br />
<br />
“Most of our boys come with a few extra pairs packed by their mothers,” she said with a flashing grin.<br />
<br />
“Now I know what to do with this big belt hanging by the robe,” I exclaimed with a waggle of my brows.  “Spank my way to respect!”<br />
<br />
She laughed through a mouthful of bread as I pulled the robe on over my head.  I was just adjusting the belt’s fit when there was a knock at my door.<br />
<br />
“Just let yourself out, sweets,” I said to Karima as I pecked her on the cheek.  “If I survive my first day, I hope to see you again soon.”<br />
<br />
The young man at the door was a rather thickly built ginger-haired fellow in a red robe and cap, with pale freckled skin and watery blue eyes.  He introduced himself as Chanz, an 8th-year student who was working as an instructor’s assistant.  He guided me out of the first floor dormitory area through the mazelike corridors of the Gray Tower until we were at the door of my first Magus instructor, Magus Tern.<br />
<br />
Magus Tern was a short round ball of energy, with cropped dark hair and rings on every finger.  I could see subtle Glyphs woven throughout the jewelry he wore, and the room he was in was filled with what looked like Smithing and Jewelsmithing tools.  One wall had a large slate affixed to it, and Tern bade me attend him at the slate.<br />
<br />
“Arch Magus Starn informed me that you already are familiar with Glyphs, and can readily see them.  Can you draw me the Glyph that seals a door against intruders?”<br />
<br />
I picked up a block of chalk and drew the Glyph for the Locking Bar, one of the many flat Glyphs I’d seen here and there.<br />
<br />
“Very close, very close,” said Tern approvingly.  He quickly sketched a Locking Bar in one smooth movement, and indeed there were several small differences to my sketch. “Now, let’s see how you do with the real thing.”<br />
<br />
Tern stepped over to a small cabinet and said “First, you must visualize pushing out your finger without moving your hand, until you can see a tiny bit of your inner vitae gleaming at the tip.”  His extended fingertip began to shine like a candle, and as he moved it, it left a trace behind as if he was drawing in the air.  “Now, you try it.”<br />
<br />
I held out my finger, willing it to move, to grow, to stretch, anything.  Nothing happened.<br />
<br />
Tern smiled and said “No one’s ever gotten this on the first try.  Here, try pushing over this coin.”  He set a coin on top of the cabinet, so that the coin was on its edge.<br />
<br />
I stood facing the coin, finger outstretched, willing my finger to push over the coin.  I was beginning to feel discouraged when I felt my Sword Hand catch, as if I’d been rubbing a bolt of silk and had snagged a rough patch of skin on it.  Suddenly a white rod slipped from my fingertip, knocking the coin onto the floor.<br />
<br />
“Excellent!” beamed Tern.  “Now draw the Locking Bar on the cabinet doors.”<br />
<br />
I touched the cabinet doors, and slipped the rod out of my fingertip as if I’d been doing it all my life.  As I moved my finger in the shape of the Locking Bar, the rod extending from my fingertip left behind a smear of light, which became the whole Glyph once I’d finished.<br />
<br />
Tern grasped the handles to the cabinet, and pulled.  The doors did not budge.  “Amazing.  Arch Magus Starn was right, you’re going to be taking classes on the Second Level by next week.  We’ll spend the rest of the morning learning how to draw some of the more useful basic Glyphs, but first, my curiosity is getting the better of me.”<br />
<br />
Tern tugged at one of the rings on his left hand, and the Glyph it held activated, sending out a warm cone of greenish light that struck the Locking Bar I’d drawn and erased it.  It was the most impressive thing I’d seen so far in the Gray Tower, that Nullifying Ring.  It was a famous artifact of the Fall of the Avatars.  Only six were known to exist in all the world.  Then Tern drew his own Locking Bar on the doors.<br />
<br />
“Can you open the doors?” Tern asked me.<br />
<br />
I sighed.  Once again, these Mages were forcing me to tip my hand, literally this time.  I positioned my Sword Hand and struck at the Glyph with the sharp invisible blade that enveloped my right hand when I willed it.  This was another gift of my unknown father, like its companion, my Shield Hand.<br />
<br />
The Glyph was cut in several places, beyond its capacity for self-repair, and the pieces fell to the floor and writhed and shrank as they sizzled down to nothing.  And then we spent the rest of the day, nay the week, studying and practicing Glyph after Glyph after Glyph.  <br />
<br />
 Magus Tern had decided that I should learn a small but useful collection of Glyphs perfectly by rote, and when I had mastered the curriculum he designed for me, within three weeks, he gave me a present:  A tiny scroll containing the entire First Level Glyph library, which was itself powered by a small persistent Glyph that caused whatever portion of the scroll was unrolled to pop out into a full three-dimensional diagram.  It was a precious gift, and I thanked Magus Tern with genuine heartfelt gratitude.<br />
<br />
 It wasn’t until I had moved on to the Second Level that I discovered that Karima was Tern’s daughter.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
