		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Lost Amulet
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1755628">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<b><center>Chapter 3</center></b><br />
<br />
 <br />
<br />
Karima and I spent much of my small stock of spare time during my First Level lessons vanishing off to various places where we could spend an evening together away from the Gray Tower.  On the night before I moved on to the Second Level, she and I went to the public house next to the Old Temple Gate at the Northeast corner of the city to hear a traveling scop of some renown named Boril of Honge.  I had heard his brand of spoken word accompanied by his swift finger picking of an eight string lyre back in my home town of Korphil’s Rest on the outskirts of Honge, and was looking forward to some music from home, as well as Karima’s pleasant company.<br />
<br />
The public house was a fine old one, converted from one of the ancient guardhouse pillars of the much-mightier Gate that once divided the now-destroyed Old Temple with the Keep of Odun that had eventually become the City of Odun once men had begun to repopulate the deserted ruins long ago.  The inside of the place was a long, wide, tall rectangular space that was sumptuously lined on three sides by a series of hardwood staircases and balconies filled with overstuffed upholstered chairs that had been bolted together into benches.  The fourth side contained a horseshoe-shaped stage with an orchestra pit inside the arms of the horseshoe.  At the base of the horseshoe, where it passed closest to the audience, sat Boril, cross-legged on the flooring of the stage, tuning his lyre to a base note he blew on the neck of a small bottle that hung from a string around his neck.<br />
<br />
Karima and I found ourselves in a very light crowd, and were able to find a pair of balcony seats on the first level very close to the center without much difficulty.  After we’d been seated for a while, and people were no longer arriving in large numbers, Boril began to strum a tune that was at once mechanical and passionate, a tune I recognized as the accompaniment to one of his most famous spoken word pieces, “The Story of How.”  And then he began to speak it, with his voice melting in our ears like warm butter as the music and his words spun their spell within our minds, and we each saw the images within ourselves of “The Story of How” as he strummed and spoke:<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				“In the beginning there was Hell; and Hell was a place where Titans battled endlessly across a void, taking great swathes of territory containing nothing, striving for no known reason.  These Titans were the Avatars of the Six Gods of Mortal Existence, mere manifestations of the actual deities who existed each on their own Planes, manifested for the express purpose of settling once and for all which deity would be the one to rule all of Creation and to demand fealty from the other five gods.<br />
<br />
“And one day the Avatars battled into range of the King of Hell’s castle, and the mere thunder and rattle of their battle was so powerful that the King of Hell was destroyed instantly on his throne.  And with the King of Hell’s death, Hell became even less substantial, and even more filled with nothingness.  The Avatars, in their battle lust, never noticed their world eroding away around them.  The first to succumb to the destruction of Hell was Earth.<br />
<br />
“Earth succumbed to the destruction of Hell, and the Avatar of Earth became the ground that is now beneath our feet.  The remaining five Avatars battled on obliviously, now trampling the body of Earth beneath their feet.  The next to succumb was Water.<br />
<br />
Water fell across Earth, covering Earth in part.  And still the battle raged on between the remaining four.  Next to succumb was Air, who fell atop of Earth and Water.  Then Fire succumbed to the destruction of Hell, and then Fire lay atop of Air, Fire’s burning corpse illuminating Earth and Water.<br />
<br />
“Oh, my sons and daughters of Woman, if only the battle had ceased then!  If only peace had found a way to bring the last two Avatars together in a new world without strife!  But alas, children of Woman, the Avatars of Red and Green Life fought on, without heeding the falling of the other four.  Each was mortally wounded, and made to separate just long enough to catch their breaths, both intending to return to the fight as soon as their strength was regained.  But it was too late.  Their wounds were too great.<br />
<br />
“Red Life’s wounds bled droplets of blood, and those droplets became the animals of the world, and Red Life’s tears of pain became Men and Women, from Red Life’s left and right eyes respectively.  And Green Life’s body dried and burst open, scattering seeds and spores around the new world, each of which became a plant.<br />
<br />
“And still the battle rages on.  Red Life devours Green Life.  Green Life sets its roots deep into the decay of Red Life.  Should either win the war, that will be the last day that Fire will shine down through Air upon Water and Earth.”
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Karima and I were both standing up and thrumming our feet on the floor with approval after his masterful conclusion.  Even in mighty Odun, the scops of Honge are without parallel.  Boril spoke five more pieces that evening, and we were so exhausted that I dropped Karima off at her boarding house and went straight home to bed so that I would not begin my Second Level training with a hangover like I did my First Level training.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
		        		<blockquote class="signature restore"><div class="signaturecontainer"><a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showpost.php?p=1325910&amp;postcount=26" target="_blank">Alikat is more right than anyone who has ever been right in the history of correctness.</a>-Istari  <img src="images/smilies/grinyes.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Grin Yes" class="inlineimg" /></div></blockquote>
				
                                        
