		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Lost Amulet
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1755790">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<center><b>Chapter 4</b></center><br />
<br />
When I made to get dressed in the morning, I was shocked to find that my robe, cap, and slippers had all changed from a light brown to a light blue.  Apparently, they were Imbued.  I began to wonder how much his dream of dead Jarn had been costing poor Arch Magus Starn.<br />
<br />
Once outside my First Floor dorm chamber, I climbed the stairs to the Second Level for the first time since my arrival at the Gray Tower three weeks ago.  Like everything else in this place, the stairs seemed to have been carved as one out of the native stone, and swept in a spiral around a pillar that was carved with intricate geometric patterns that repeated and themselves formed larger patterns as the eye swept outwards.  Once at the Second Floor&#8217;s delicate exit arch, I paused and drew the Glyph for Seeking, and then I spoke the name of he who was to be sought: &#8220;Chanz.&#8221;<br />
<br />
The Glyph had a loop that had a brightly glowing spot that guided me faithfully through a complex series of turns in the obvious labyrinth beyond the arch.  As soon as I had opened the door to which it led me, and laid eyes on Chanz, the Glyph of Seeking faded away.<br />
<br />
Chanz was one of Magus Tern&#8217;s 8th-year student teachers, having had the honor of completing his 7th year of study by turning in an independent studies scroll to Tern that had somewhat revolutionized Summoning by vastly simplifying the required Protection elements with his discovery that no more than five Glyphs would take effect no matter how many were in place.  Magus Tern had joked once that &#8220;Chanz of Kersiph has saved Mages dozens of minutes!&#8221;  <br />
<br />
&#8220;Good, let&#8217;s get right to work,&#8221; Chanz said briskly as I entered.  &#8220;Draw me the Glyph for Lightning but don&#8217;t activate it.&#8221;<br />
<br />
I drew a passable Glyph of Lightning, and grasped it gingerly so as to not squeeze the activation lines together.  Chanz nodded, and then he drew a Glyph I&#8217;d not yet learned, a spiral tube that doubled back to a part that looked a lot like the door openers on the Gray Tower&#8217;s interior doors.<br />
<br />
&#8220;Can you copy this one?&#8221; he asked me.<br />
<br />
It took a couple of false starts, but eventually my hands learned to do the dance almost on their own, and I almost casually fashioned a near exact copy of the complex Glyph that Chanz had drawn.  Chanz smiled in approval, then he drew his own Glyph of Lightning with one hand in an incredibly deft movement, and then, with exaggerated movements so I could see everything he did, he fitted the Glyph of Lightning neatly into the other Glyph as if it was a hand in a glove.  Then he pointed the tubular narrow double-spiral down the length of the long room (it looked like a walled-off section of corridor, really) and squeezed the activation lines on the Glyph of Lightning.<br />
<br />
A bolt of lightning corkscrewed out of the other Glyph, spiraling straight down the length of the room, where it struck a straw combat practice dummy that was standing in a row of the same at the far wall.  It exploded into a cloud of burning straw, and the two dummies on either side began to smolder from the heat.<br />
<br />
&#8220;Interested in Spells, are you?&#8221; Chanz turned to me and asked with a grin.  &#8220;That was your first Spell.  A small harmless Glyph of Lightning added to a Firing Rail becomes a powerful bolt of lightning directed at a distant target.  The Firing Rail can then be reloaded with any of a number of elemental Glyphs.&#8221;<br />
<br />
Chanz&#8217;s grin was infectious as I quickly drew a Glyph of Frost, loaded it into the Firing Rail, and encased one of the still-smoldering target dummies in a block of solid white.  <br />
<br />
Four weeks later, I had completed Chanz&#8217;s Second Level curriculum, and my belt was hung with an array of useful Spells, and was beginning to look like a Mage, at least, even if an overgrown junior one.<br />
<br />
One morning I awoke and my robe had changed color again, this time to a deep royal blue, and I knew to seek Chanz upon the Third Level of the Gray Tower for the next phase of my instruction.<br />
&#8195;
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
