		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Lost Amulet
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1755795">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<b><center><font size="3">Chapter 5</font></center></b><br />
<br />
While I was spending my days with Chanz, I was spending my evenings with Magus Tern, helping him with some big mysterious project he was undertaking at the ruins of the Old Temple.  I helped him erect a shed at a spot he’d chosen on the grounds, a place on the side closest to the walls of Odun.  Once the shed was built, I helped him bring all manner of equipment and supplies from his workshop on the First Level of the Gray Tower into the shed, including work benches and tool boxes and stack after stack of ceramic things that looked like oxbows with thick flanges at the ends.  As soon as we’d brought over the last of at least three sixes of six arm-length arc-shaped ceramic sculptures, Tern thanked me and told me to go have fun and enjoy the city, for my services would no longer be needed.<br />
<br />
Naturally, I took him up on his offer, and began spending my evenings with Karima, enjoying all of the finer points of Odun together with her, as she knew the city like a lover.  There was no dice den, no party house, no sensual spa that she was not aware of.  And everybody seemed to know Karima wherever we went; yet the reckoning I’d been expecting to come, an angry Tern destroying me on the spot for taking advantage of his daughter, never came to pass.  Whatever Magus Tern was doing in the shed we’d built, it was keeping him supernally busy.<br />
<br />
The Third Level had me mixing potion bases containing special sympathetic ingredients plus raw vitae, pouring it into vials, and then using a Carrier Glyph to destroy a Spell or Glyph, and dissolving the Carrier Glyph into one of the vials of potion base.  This gave the Spell or Glyph inside the potion easier storage options, plus it could be activated by anyone who drank it, even if they were unable to so much as see a Glyph.  Since poppy milk was so often considered a sympathetic ingredient, I assumed that Mages also loved to drink poppy milk and took any excuse they could.<br />
<br />
Four weeks of Potions instruction, and Chanz told me to expect my robe to be gold colored the next morning.  I climbed to the Fourth Level of the Gray Tower in my gold robe the next day with a medicine pouch filled with potion vials hanging from the left side of my belt.  After finding Chanz in a large square room deep in the maze of the Fourth Level, he set to showing me the basics of drawing a Circle of Protection on the floor.  As long as I stood within that circle, there was very little magic, either human or otherwise, that could do me any harm.  Then Chanz drilled me for two sixes of days in how to draw Glyphs of Control and Glyphs of Summoning.  Finally the day came when he decided that I was ready to draw my first Summoning Circle together with a Summoning Glyph and a Control Glyph outside a Circle of Protection, step into the inner Circle, and activate the entire Spell.<br />
<br />
And that was the day that my idyllic sense of comfort within the Gray Tower was replaced by a growing foreboding, for that was the day that I learned too much.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
