			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Lost Amulet
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1755888">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<b><center><font size="3">Chapter 6</font></center></b><br />
<br />
I’m still not sure why, out of six choices of different bottom-tier sprites, I decided to summon a Swarm of Fleshlings.  Perhaps it was an inward sense of perversity, or, worse, a deep hidden desire to attack my own success.  But it was a Swarm that I chose.<br />
<br />
I drew the Circle of Protection, then the Circle of Summoning, then the Summoning Glyph, and finally five Control Glyphs.  I had chosen Obedience, Fear, Peaceful Means, Lawful, and Truthspeak.  These were commonly used for such low-level instructional Summonses.  <br />
<br />
I stepped into the Protective Circle.  Chanz was standing in his own Protective Circle that he’d drawn outside of my Spell.  The room was sealed with Glyphs designed to prevent passage of sprites, in case I somehow fouled up.  I bent down and activated the Summoning spell.<br />
<br />
The air in the room seemed to waver, and from the floor inside the Summoning Circle arose the silhouette of a fat man with no legs and a hundred stunted arms coming out of him, all beneath his two large main arms that protruded normally from his shoulders, so that he looked like a human jellyfish, standing on arm-shaped tendrils.  Then this vision of the Avatar of Flesh broke apart into shards, each of which was a tiny little thumb-sized version of the Avatar of Flesh, which flapped their tiny stunted arms in order to fly like deranged pale bumblebees, in a spiral vortex of tiny Fleshlings.<br />
<br />
Chanz thrummed his feet in appreciation for my successful Summoning.  We shared a triumphant grin as the Swarm of Fleshlings remained within the Summoning Circle instead of flying into our faces and attacking our eyes as I’d half-expected them to do.  But then the Swarm of Fleshlings opened all of its tiny mouths at once, and spoke.<br />
<br />
“Kiril, Son of Woman, I bear tidings from your Father:  Beware the actions of wise fools!  The rotund one courts the end of all!  All of existence is on the brink of a war of total destruction.  The armies of the Planes are massing to march on your world.  The Avatars seek to return from their Fall, and to conclude their contest.  The new order of existence will be no more if they succeed.  Finally, this – there are factions within the ranks of their thralls that would deny the avatars their desire to return.”<br />
<br />
I was not too shocked to ask: “Who is my father?”<br />
<br />
“We bear no names, for when we meet, we are already known to one another.  No labels would suffice,” replied the Swarm unhelpfully.  The Swarm was spectacularly unhelpful, being perhaps the most incurious sprite in the entire Fleshworld.  It knew nothing more of my father, of the Plane of Red Life’s preparations for war against the world of men, or of any details about vying factions of sprites.  Eventually I released the Swarm to return to the Fleshworld, and Chanz and I made preparations to Summon a higher level of sprite.<br />
<br />
But apparently my Swarm was the very last time that anyone in the Gray Tower was able to successfully summon any sprite from any of the six Planes.  The Planes were keeping their secrets in the run-up to war.  The capacity to form a contract with the denizens of the Planes had been withdrawn by the powers that ruled within the Planes, it seems.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
