		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: The Lost Amulet
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1755960">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<center><b><font size="3">Chapter 7</font></b></center><br />
 <br />
After spending the rest of the morning attempting to Summon any sprite from any Plane and failing every attempt, Chanz went to seek the Arch Magus to tell him what had occurred:  we had received a dire warning of a Planar war upon the world of men, and after that all communications between our world and the Planes had been cut off.  I last saw Chanz running up the stairway towards the Ninth Level, where the Magi had their offices and apartments, taking the stairs two and three at a time.<br />
 <br />
I myself headed downstairs, intending to head over to the Cup &amp; Plate for a mug or two of their strongest beer.  I stopped for a few moments to talk to Karima at the reception desk, and while we were making small talk Magus Tern walked in from the front entrance, looking distracted and disheveled.<br />
 <br />
&#8220;Magus Tern!&#8221; I called to him as he passed.   &#8220;Have you a moment to speak?&#8221;  I intended to tell him the events of the morning, as he was Arch Magus Starn&#8217;s closest advisor.<br />
 <br />
&#8220;Sorry, my boy, but I&#8217;m afraid I&#8217;m positively overwhelmed at the moment, it will have to wait,&#8221; Tern said, rubbing his chest nervously and glancing down the hallway towards the staircase.<br />
 <br />
&#8220;Is there anything I can do to help?&#8221; I asked. <br />
 <br />
He looked at me as if he had only just recognized me.  &#8220;That&#8217;s very thoughtful of you, Kiril, but I&#8217;m afraid that only my, uh, collaborators can assist me at this phase of the project, and I haven&#8217;t been able to, erm, reach them today.  Very thoughtful of you&#8230;&#8221; he trailed off, and then suddenly began walking briskly to the stairs as if he&#8217;d forgotten he was in conversation.  Karima and I watched him disappear around the corner, both of us with concerned expressions on our faces.  I took my leave of Karima and went over to the Cup &amp; Plate and managed to relax enough to lose two silver pieces playing darts with one of the local punters. <br />
 <br />
I awoke the next morning to a banging on my door that made my head feel like it was being hammered on instead of the thick wooden door.   Chanz had come to tell me that my morning&#8217;s lesson had been canceled, but told me that he was not allowed to speak of yesterday&#8217;s events with anyone other than the Gray Tower&#8217;s faculty.<br />
 <br />
Since the Summoning lessons of the Fourth Level had been rendered impossible by circumstance, Chanz advanced me to the Fifth Level, my robe changing to a smoky orange color.  I no longer had the sense of happy satisfaction that a change in robe color had brought me, though, because of the news that had been delivered to me by the Swarm of Fleshlings.  A foreboding of war against the very order of existence has a way of coming between a man and his happiness.<br />
 <br />
My first morning on the Fifth Level, I was to seek my new instructor, the Gray Tower&#8217;s official Instructor in the Arts of Defense and Offense.  I was told his name only, which was Chalarn.  After the Glyph of Seeking had led me to Chalarn&#8217;s classroom, I found the inside to be a large square open space with workbenches and tall work stools on all four walls, everywhere but the doorway. <br />
 <br />
The slender dark-haired man who the Seeker&#8217;s loop had indicated was Chalarn was standing near the center of the room, facing a tall nervous-looking teen.  He turned towards me when I walked through the doorway, to the visible relief of the teen.<br />
<br />
&#8220;You must be Kiril.  Welcome to the Fifth Level, where we instruct our pupils in the Defensive and Offensive Arts.  Please find yourself an empty seat and observe, I&#8217;ve put Glyphs of Limiting on our Firing Rails, and my opponent and I are going to exchange fire until one of us fails to avoid being hit.  Be aware that at least one bystander is hit in every one of these sparring matches, nobody in this room is safe from pain.&#8221;  He smiled coldly, and turned back towards the teen, who gulped visibly and clutched his capped Firing Rail miserably.<br />
<br />
I hastened to the nearest empty work stool, leaning my back against the workbench behind me as I settled in to watch the match.  I was surprised to see that I recognized one of the boys seated around the room as a rather unpleasant bully from my own home town of Korphil&#8217;s Rest.<br />
<br />
Magus Chalarn saluted the teen, who returned the salute with far less grace.  As the teen saluted, I saw clearly that he was already attacking by noting the familiar thoughtless rictus I&#8217;d seen on at least a hundred faces in my short career as a Spear for Hire.  I looked at his left hand, and the sneaky little bastard was holding it not by the double-spiral barrel, as the left hand would normally have done, but was instead holding the part normally gripped by the right hand, and had raised the barrel enough so that it was aimed at Chalarn&#8217;s slippers.  At that moment, just as he was lowering his right hand from the salute, the teen fired a bolt of flame at Chalarn&#8217;s feet, but Chalarn had somehow gotten his Firing Rail into position one-handed as well, and had fired a bolt of frost at the same moment, and the two bolts struck each other a few feet from Chalarn&#8217;s toes, so that all that struck Chalarn was a puff of water vapor.<br />
<br />
The match was now a foregone conclusion, as Magus Chalarn drew a Glyph of Lightning so rapidly that he had it loaded into his Firing Rail before the teen had finished drawing his Glyph of Stone, and the teen went down to his knees wrapped in writhing serpents of lightning.  The entire match had lasted for perhaps four seconds.  That was the longest match of the morning, and Magus Chalarn lectured each fallen opponent on exactly where they had gone wrong and exactly how they could have gotten a lick in first.  I had not yet had my turn in the center of the room with Chalarn when we broke for lunch.<br />
<br />
In the First Level outside of the student dormitory area was the student Dining Hall.  The food was unremarkable, but I took most of my midday meals there out of convenience.  As I approached the entrance to the Dining Hall, I heard a voice behind me call my name: &#8220;Kiril of the Mad Eyes!&#8221;<br />
 <br />
I turned, and after a moment I recognized one of the two who approached me as Ferril of Honge, a boy from my home town who I had noticed at class.  The other boy had been one of the boys who had sparred with Magus Chalarn that morning.  I remembered his name as being something like Kerinern, obviously a native of Odun.<br />
<br />
&#8220;Hello, Ferril, why so formal?  You can just call me Kiril.&#8221; I said coolly.  We had never gotten along when we were lads, when I&#8217;d been sold as a Guard&#8217;s Apprentice I&#8217;d been relieved to have gotten out of Korphil&#8217;s Rest before I&#8217;d wound up killing Ferril.  I was not happy to see him now, familiar face from home or not.<br />
<br />
&#8220;Then why don&#8217;t I just call you Uncanny,&#8221; Ferril sneered.  He and Kerinern exchanged a look that my trained eyes recognized as pack hunting communication.  Kerinern began to walk, ostensibly towards the Dining Hall, but he had that rictus on his face that spoke of an intent other than dining.  I split my attention between the two, and when Kerinern turned back towards me, raising an uncapped Firing Rail, Ferril also raised his Firing Rail, which had obviously had its Glyph of Limiting removed.<br />
<br />
I raised my Shield Hand towards the barrel of Kerinern&#8217;s Firing Rail, and when he fired a missile of stone at me, it bounced harmlessly off of my palm and fell to the floor.  I was swinging my Sword Hand upwards towards Ferril&#8217;s Firing Rail, and before he got it pulled up into an angle that had a chance of striking my lower body, my Sword Hand sliced his Firing Rail in two, and all of a sudden Ferril was holding nothing but a bare and harmless Glyph of Lightning, and his Firing Rail was in sizzling flapping pieces on the ground, dissolving into nothing as I balled my right hand into an ordinary fist and slammed Ferril in the left temple, stunning him and dropping him to his hands and knees. <br />
 <br />
Kerinern was in the middle of drawing a Glyph of Lightning when my slippered foot caught him square in the balls, and while both of them were on the floor like a pair of babes, I walked into the Dining Hall and had a rather mediocre lunch.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
